{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496483"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:48:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:48:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1368"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1368"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.08,0.12,0.05,0.64]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1368"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72828"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1368"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1368"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58298"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"153"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"2115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4693"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5215"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11025"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46082"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72828"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man is undergoing a laparotomy for an obstructing gastric cancer. During the exploratory part of the procedure, the following structure is noted (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the typical mode of presentation for this finding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Colicky, generalised abdominal pain","Constant right iliac fossa pain","Passage of altered blood per rectum","Sudden onset, generalised abdominal pain","Incidental finding at surgery"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a Meckel\u0027s diverticulum. This embryonic remnant is a relatively common incidental intra-operative finding, occurring in about 2% of the population. It is a true diverticulum that results from incomplete obliteration of the vitelline duct during development. A Meckel\u0027s diverticulum can be associated with various symptoms, particularly in childhood. Signs and symptoms associated with the diverticulum are uncommon, however, they can present as acute gastrointestinal haemorrhage (eg. \u003Cstrong\u003Epassage of blood per rectum)\u003C/strong\u003E, inflammation, perforation or small bowel obstruction. When symptoms do arise, they are often due to the presence of ectopic tissue (eg parietal cells) in the diverticulum. In adulthood a Meckel\u0027s diverticulum is usually asymptomatic and perhaps found incidentally when the patient is having an unrelated abdominal procedure. When \u003Cstrong\u003Efound incidentally\u003C/strong\u003E and with the appearance of a wide neck - such as shown in the photograph - they should be left alone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Meckel\u0027s diverticulum is a congenital diverticulum resulting from incomplete obliteration of the vitelline duct","Commonly a incidental finding during intra-operative exploration"],"references":["Negm YAH. Human malformations and related anomalies, second edition. Arch Dis Child. 2007;92(3):280. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2083405/","Sagar J, Kumar V, Shah DK. Meckel\u0027s diverticulum: a systematic review. J R Soc Med 2006;99:501. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1592061/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58298"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1368"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14882"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14882"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f77f999f-cee4-47d6-9839-bd5a411bec1d.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f77f999f-cee4-47d6-9839-bd5a411bec1d.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":386}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58298"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T09:03:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-10T12:27:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1368"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72828"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{